SIMPLE: rouse
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rouse
<hw>Rouse</hw> <pr>(rouz <it>or</it> rous)</pr>, <pos>v. i. & t.</pos>
<ety>[Perhaps the same word as <ets>rouse</ets> to start up,
⟦ldquo⟧buckle to.⟦rdquo⟧]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To pull or haul
strongly and all together, as upon a rope, without the assistance of
mechanical appliances.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rouse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rouse
<hw>Rouse</hw> <pr>(rouz)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. D.
<ets>roes</ets> drunkeness, icel. <ets>r⟦umac⟧ss</ets>, Sw.
<ets>rus</ets>, G. <ets>rauchen</ets>, and also E. <ets>rouse</ets>,
v.t., <ets>rush</ets>, v.i. Cf. <er>Row</er> a disturbance.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A bumper in honor of a toast or health.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A carousal; a festival; a drinking frolic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fill the cup, and fill the can,⟦br⟧
Have a <qex>rouse</qex> before the morn.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rouse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Rouse
<hw>Rouse</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Roused</conjf> <pr>(rouzd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Rousing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Probably of Scan. origin; cf.
Sw. <ets>rusa</ets> to rush, Dan. <ets>ruse</ets>, AS.
<ets>hre⟦oacute⟧san</ets> to fall, rush. Cf. <er>Rush</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to start from a covert or
lurking place; <as>as, to <ex>rouse</ex> a deer or other animal of the
chase</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like wild boars late <qex>roused</qex> out of the brakes.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Rouse</qex> the fleet hart, and cheer the opening hound.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wake from sleep or repose; <as>as, to
<ex>rouse</ex> one early or suddenly</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To excite to lively thought or action from a state
of idleness, languor, stupidity, or indifference; <as>as, to
<ex>rouse</ex> the faculties, passions, or emotions</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>rouse</qex> up a people, the most phlegmatic of any in
Christendom.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To put in motion; to stir up; to agitate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Blustering winds, which all night long⟦br⟧
Had <qex>roused</qex> the sea.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To raise; to make erect.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser. Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rouse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Rouse
<hw>Rouse</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To get or start up; to
rise.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Night's black agents to their preys do <qex>rouse</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To awake from sleep or repose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Morpheus <qex>rouses</qex> from his bed.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be exited to thought or action from a state of
indolence or inattention.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rouser</ent>⟦br⟧
